1. The Preprocessing PipelineWhen a document (movie overview or book description) is ingested—or when a user submits a search query—it undergoes a strict, sequential five-stage pipeline:
[Raw Data] ➔ [Lowercasing] ➔ [Regex Sanitization] ➔ [Tokenization] ➔ [Stopword/Length Filter] ➔ [Porter Stemming]
Case Normalization (Lowercasing): Every character is converted to lowercase to eliminate case sensitivity. This ensures that "Batman", "batman", and "BATMAN" map to the exact same token.Regex Sanitization: The engine applies the regular expression [^a-z0-9\s] to strip out punctuation, special characters, and symbols, replacing them with empty spaces. This preserves alphanumeric characters while isolating core words.Whitespace Tokenization: The clean string is split along whitespace boundaries, converting a continuous block of text into an array of individual word strings.Stopword Filtering & Length Constraints: Common English words that carry high frequency but low informational value (e.g., "the", "is", "and") are discarded using NLTK's standard stopword corpus. Additionally, a strict length filter drops any token where:$$\text{length} \le 1$$This eliminates lingering single-letter noise (like random punctuation artifacts) from bloating the index.Morphological Stemming: The remaining tokens are processed via the Porter Stemmer algorithm. This reduces words to their base or root form by stripping common suffixes (e.g., "running", "runs", and "ran" are collapsed to "run").
2. Inverted Index Structural DesignInstead of a flat structural layout, CineReads implements a Positional Inverted Index. It is constructed in-memory using a nested dictionary structure via Python's 
     {
    "dark": {
        104: [3, 42],        # Term appears in Doc 104 at word offsets 3 and 42
        1829: [12]           # Term appears in Doc 1829 at word offset 12
    },
    "knight": {
        104: [4, 87]
    }
}
Every unique stem points to a nested directory of Document IDs, which in turn point to a dynamic integer array tracking the exact word placements within that document.
3. Technical Justifications & Depth of KnowledgeChoosing this architecture involves balancing structural complexity, processing speed, and memory usage:Why a Positional Index instead of a Standard Inverted Index?A standard inverted index only tracks document presence (term -> [doc_ids]). While lightweight, it leaves the system blind to word order.The Justification: CineReads requires positional tracking to support complex search features. Without storing integer positions, it would be impossible to run exact phrase queries (e.g., matching "The Dark Knight" exactly rather than finding documents where "dark" and "knight" appear pages apart).Furthermore, this layout powers our Context-Aware Sliding Window Snippet Generator, allowing the backend to instantly scan word locations and extract the exact paragraph snippet with the highest density of matching query terms.Stemming (Porter) vs. LemmatizationThe Justification: Lemmatization relies on deep morphological analysis and Part-of-Speech (POS) tagging, which introduces severe computational overhead during large-scale ingestion. The Porter Stemmer operates on algorithmic, heuristic-based suffix stripping. While occasionally crude (e.g., truncation anomalies), it is incredibly fast and achieves a significant reduction in vocabulary size, maximizing hit ratios across both movie and book plots.In-Memory Dictionary Architecture (defaultdict)The Justification: Python's native dictionary is implemented as a highly optimized hash table with $O(1)$ average-case lookup time complexity. By nesting these dictionaries, lookups for candidate evaluation run in:$$O(|Q|)$$Where $|Q|$ represents the number of terms in the query. This isolates query times from the total size of the database, keeping search latency in the millisecond range.
